1
00:00:03,281 --> 00:00:06,641
DOCTOR: Space. The final frontier.

2
00:00:12,921 --> 00:00:16,241
"Final"” because it wants to kill us.

3
00:00:17,361 --> 00:00:19,681
Sometimes we forget that.

4
00:00:19,761 --> 00:00:22,161
Start taking it all for granted.

5
00:00:22,281 --> 00:00:25,321
The suits, the ships,
the little bubbles of safety,

6
00:00:26,321 --> 00:00:28,281
as they protect us from the void.

7
00:00:31,161 --> 00:00:34,281
But the void is always waiting.

8
00:00:42,401 --> 00:00:45,401
WOMAN: (OVER RADIO)
This isn't the best timing, I know that.

9
00:00:45,481 --> 00:00:47,161
But, typical me.

10
00:00:48,601 --> 00:00:49,801
-Maybe it's because...
-(BEEPING)

11
00:00:49,881 --> 00:00:51,481
AUTOMATED FEMALE VOICE:
Oxygen levels critical.

12
00:00:51,561 --> 00:00:53,881
WOMAN: Everything is so messed up,

13
00:00:54,681 --> 00:00:58,241
the trivial stuff just falls
away. (EXHALES)

14
00:01:00,481 --> 00:01:05,281
You realise life can be so brief.

15
00:01:05,921 --> 00:01:10,401
And so, I just want to tell you,
if we do get through this...

16
00:01:12,641 --> 00:01:15,441
(CHUCKLES) I want to have a baby
with you.

17
00:01:19,121 --> 00:01:20,761
(ALARM CHIMING)

18
00:01:24,081 --> 00:01:25,281
(SIGHS)

19
00:01:25,921 --> 00:01:28,961
(PANTING) And as soon
as my radio's fixed,

20
00:01:29,921 --> 00:01:31,161
I'm going to tell you just that.

21
00:01:31,241 --> 00:01:33,001
AUTOMATED FEMALE VOICE: Mag boots on.

22
00:01:34,721 --> 00:01:36,761
(PANTING)

23
00:01:38,201 --> 00:01:39,361
AUTOMATED FEMALE VOICE: Mag boots on.

24
00:01:44,281 --> 00:01:46,961
Nearly there. (PANTING)

25
00:01:52,881 --> 00:01:54,801
Can you hear me? Ivan?

26
00:01:55,001 --> 00:01:57,601
I still can't hear you, love.
You're wasting your breath.

27
00:02:01,241 --> 00:02:03,681
-The one thing we can't waste.
-(BEEPING)

28
00:02:19,521 --> 00:02:20,801
(GRUNTS)

29
00:02:25,801 --> 00:02:27,321
IVAN: Need to bypass it.

30
00:02:42,641 --> 00:02:44,641
-(PNEUMATIC HISSING)
-No! No! No! No!

31
00:02:44,721 --> 00:02:46,441
(SCREAMS) No! No! No!

32
00:02:47,721 --> 00:02:48,961
(MOTOR WHIRRING)

33
00:02:50,241 --> 00:02:51,241
(IVAN LAUGHS)

34
00:02:53,161 --> 00:02:54,281
Yeah!

35
00:02:58,721 --> 00:03:00,041
(GASPING)

36
00:03:01,761 --> 00:03:02,881
(BOOTS THUDDING)

37
00:03:05,041 --> 00:03:06,561
-No/
-(BEEPING)

38
00:03:06,641 --> 00:03:07,961
(SCREAMS) No!

39
00:03:10,121 --> 00:03:12,121
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

40
00:03:53,041 --> 00:03:54,841
So how does space kill you?

41
00:03:57,561 --> 00:03:58,681
I'm glad you asked.

42
00:04:00,281 --> 00:04:02,681
The main problem is pressure.

43
00:04:04,441 --> 00:04:05,481
There isn't any.

44
00:04:06,041 --> 00:04:08,401
So don't hold your breath
or your lungs will explode.

45
00:04:09,681 --> 00:04:11,441
Blood vessels rupture.

46
00:04:12,841 --> 00:04:15,121
Exposed areas swell.

47
00:04:16,361 --> 00:04:17,361
Fun fact...

48
00:04:17,961 --> 00:04:22,401
The boiling temperature of water
is much lower in a vacuum.

49
00:04:22,481 --> 00:04:23,601
Which means...

50
00:04:25,161 --> 00:04:26,161
...that your sweat

51
00:04:26,361 --> 00:04:28,721
and your saliva will boil.

52
00:04:30,161 --> 00:04:32,121
As will the fluid around your eyes.

53
00:04:33,801 --> 00:04:35,881
You won't notice any of this

54
00:04:36,041 --> 00:04:37,601
because 15 seconds in,

55
00:04:37,681 --> 00:04:40,801
you passed out as oxygen bubbles
formed in your blood,

56
00:04:40,881 --> 00:04:42,001
and 90 seconds in...

57
00:04:47,481 --> 00:04:48,681
You're dead.

58
00:04:51,321 --> 00:04:52,361
Any questions?

59
00:04:55,761 --> 00:04:56,761
Yes.

60
00:04:57,721 --> 00:04:59,321
What's this got to do
with crop rotation?

61
00:05:01,081 --> 00:05:03,921
Er, I don't know.
But space is great, isn't it?

62
00:05:04,201 --> 00:05:05,281
NARDOLE: You're missing it, aren't you?

63
00:05:05,841 --> 00:05:08,201
-Crop rotation?
-Space.

64
00:05:10,841 --> 00:05:13,641
I'm worried you're thinking
about taking another trip, sir.

65
00:05:13,961 --> 00:05:15,721
I'm here, I'm guarding the vault.
What do you want from me?

66
00:05:16,481 --> 00:05:17,561
The truth.

67
00:05:18,241 --> 00:05:19,561
Don't be unreasonable.

68
00:05:28,601 --> 00:05:29,601
(CHUCKLES)

69
00:05:29,761 --> 00:05:30,801
Space.

70
00:05:31,241 --> 00:05:34,041
Going to space is exactly like camping.

71
00:05:34,561 --> 00:05:36,561
-BILL: Is it?
-Er, or no.

72
00:05:37,081 --> 00:05:38,721
-BILL: Okay.
-Well, in a way, yes.

73
00:05:39,281 --> 00:05:41,721
-Great.
-Too much between you and the outside

74
00:05:41,801 --> 00:05:43,121
and you might as well stay home.

75
00:05:43,201 --> 00:05:44,201
To really feel it,

76
00:05:44,281 --> 00:05:47,041
you need the space equivalent
of a wafer-thin sleeping bag

77
00:05:47,121 --> 00:05:49,001
and a leaky two-man tent.

78
00:05:49,081 --> 00:05:50,081
So, pick a campsite.

79
00:05:51,841 --> 00:05:53,561
-Got any reviews?
-What?

80
00:05:53,961 --> 00:05:55,001
You know, like for restaurants.

81
00:05:55,241 --> 00:05:57,521
"Waiter was a bit handsy,
lasagne gave me the trots. Two stars.”

82
00:05:57,601 --> 00:05:58,601
Strangely, no.

83
00:06:00,321 --> 00:06:02,281
(EXCITEDLY) Oh, I don't know. That one.

84
00:06:02,441 --> 00:06:04,801
Ah, yes.
Well, er, possibly we could go there

85
00:06:04,881 --> 00:06:06,521
and pitch our tent next
to the toilet block.

86
00:06:06,721 --> 00:06:08,721
How about something a bit more exciting?

87
00:06:11,561 --> 00:06:13,361
-(BEEPING)
-BILL: What's that?

88
00:06:13,441 --> 00:06:15,241
That is my theme tune.

89
00:06:16,201 --> 00:06:18,321
Otherwise known as a distress call.

90
00:06:18,401 --> 00:06:19,721
You like distress calls?

91
00:06:19,881 --> 00:06:22,361
You only really see
the true face of the universe

92
00:06:22,441 --> 00:06:23,961
when it's asking for your help.

93
00:06:24,041 --> 00:06:26,361
NARDOLE: Haven't seen my true
face in years.

94
00:06:26,961 --> 00:06:28,441
Swapped it for this one on the run.

95
00:06:28,521 --> 00:06:31,081
Oh, look, Bill. It's Nardole.
What a lovely surprise.

96
00:06:32,121 --> 00:06:34,161
I thought I sent you to Birmingham
for a packet of crisps.

97
00:06:34,241 --> 00:06:36,441
Yeah, I saw through your cunning ruse.

98
00:06:36,521 --> 00:06:38,841
Yes, well, if you will go thinking
for yourself. What do you want?

99
00:06:38,921 --> 00:06:40,241
I was given strict instructions

100
00:06:40,681 --> 00:06:42,281
to keep you at the university.

101
00:06:42,761 --> 00:06:44,041
-DOCTOR: Who by?
-You.

102
00:06:44,441 --> 00:06:46,081
Well, you're not doing
a very good job, are you?

103
00:06:46,161 --> 00:06:47,201
I'll overlook it this once.

104
00:06:47,721 --> 00:06:49,081
Do you know what this is?

105
00:06:49,561 --> 00:06:50,961
If it is not crisps, you're sacked.

106
00:06:51,081 --> 00:06:52,921
Fluid link K-57.

107
00:06:53,041 --> 00:06:55,921
Removed it from the TARDIS
the other night after your lecture.

108
00:06:56,241 --> 00:06:58,201
DOCTOR: That is very untrusting.

109
00:06:58,321 --> 00:06:59,721
NARDOLE: You took an oath, sir.

110
00:06:59,801 --> 00:07:01,521
The vault cannot be unguarded.

111
00:07:01,761 --> 00:07:02,761
Listen to Mr Boring.

112
00:07:02,961 --> 00:07:04,441
I'm acting under your orders.

113
00:07:04,601 --> 00:07:05,601
See how reliable I am?

114
00:07:05,921 --> 00:07:07,001
What's a fluid link?

115
00:07:07,081 --> 00:07:10,121
No idea. But the TARDIS
can't go anywhere without it.

116
00:07:10,601 --> 00:07:11,841
-Who told you that?
-You did.

117
00:07:11,921 --> 00:07:13,201
-Exactly.
-(SNAPS FINGERS)

118
00:07:13,841 --> 00:07:16,041
-What...
-Teach you to trust me.

119
00:07:16,561 --> 00:07:17,561
No.

120
00:07:17,761 --> 00:07:18,921
I'm docking your pay for this.

121
00:07:19,241 --> 00:07:20,481
(WHOOSHING)

122
00:07:21,361 --> 00:07:22,361
(LAUGHING)

123
00:07:28,321 --> 00:07:29,561
(DOOR CREAKING OPEN)

124
00:07:31,081 --> 00:07:32,241
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER BUZZING)

125
00:07:33,761 --> 00:07:35,001
(BUZZING STOPS)

126
00:07:36,641 --> 00:07:37,681
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER BUZZING)

127
00:07:37,761 --> 00:07:39,881
-I'm a bit cross with you, sir.
-Noted.

128
00:07:40,521 --> 00:07:41,681
Scored out and forgotten.

129
00:07:42,761 --> 00:07:44,721
Wait. There's no oxygen.

130
00:07:44,961 --> 00:07:46,001
What?

131
00:07:46,481 --> 00:07:47,481
Well, how come we're breathing?

132
00:07:47,641 --> 00:07:49,481
Air shell around the TARDIS. Hang on.

133
00:07:50,001 --> 00:07:51,401
(AIR WHOOSHING)

134
00:07:52,441 --> 00:07:53,921
(ALARM BEEPING)

135
00:07:54,641 --> 00:07:57,001
Now there's a really big air shell
around the TARDIS.

136
00:07:57,561 --> 00:07:58,721
How big?

137
00:07:59,401 --> 00:08:00,601
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER BUZZING)

138
00:08:05,201 --> 00:08:06,441
Big enough for a stroll.

139
00:08:08,201 --> 00:08:09,321
So cocky.

140
00:08:14,441 --> 00:08:15,601
BILL: Why aren't we floating?

141
00:08:15,681 --> 00:08:16,801
DOCTOR: Artificial gravity.

142
00:08:25,081 --> 00:08:26,441
Doesn't feel like space.

143
00:08:30,681 --> 00:08:31,681
Ah!

144
00:08:35,761 --> 00:08:38,081
Now it feels like space.

145
00:08:39,161 --> 00:08:41,801
DOCTOR: Look at this classic design.

146
00:08:42,241 --> 00:08:43,681
Pressure seals.

147
00:08:44,321 --> 00:08:45,321
Hinges.

148
00:08:45,441 --> 00:08:46,521
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER BUZZING)

149
00:08:46,641 --> 00:08:48,521
None of that "schuck-schuck" nonsense.

150
00:08:49,041 --> 00:08:51,241
Space doors are supposed to go
"schuck-schuck."

151
00:08:51,801 --> 00:08:53,561
-Not "Mmm..."
-(DOOR HUMMING OPEN)

152
00:08:56,121 --> 00:08:57,881
-Are you gonna be like this all day?
-Yeah.

153
00:08:57,961 --> 00:08:59,641
Till you're back where you should be.

154
00:08:59,721 --> 00:09:00,721
Er, guys.

155
00:09:01,801 --> 00:09:03,361
-NARDOLE: Hmm?
-(DOOR OPENING)

156
00:09:06,761 --> 00:09:07,881
Hello?

157
00:09:13,281 --> 00:09:14,641
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

158
00:09:28,161 --> 00:09:29,281
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER BUZZING)

159
00:09:30,481 --> 00:09:31,641
He's dead.

160
00:09:32,041 --> 00:09:34,001
Well, how can he be dead?
He's standing up.

161
00:09:35,641 --> 00:09:36,641
Er, no.

162
00:09:36,841 --> 00:09:38,081
His suit's standing up.

163
00:09:38,681 --> 00:09:40,881
-He's just along for the ride.
-Oh, God.

164
00:09:42,281 --> 00:09:43,481
What, it's standing for him?

165
00:09:43,761 --> 00:09:47,761
Gyro stabilisers, magnetic boots,
gloves, on-board computer.

166
00:09:47,841 --> 00:09:49,681
It could run, jump and update
his Facebook.

167
00:09:51,761 --> 00:09:53,441
Death, where is thy sting?

168
00:09:54,281 --> 00:09:55,321
So...

169
00:09:55,401 --> 00:09:56,921
Back to the TARDIS?

170
00:09:57,481 --> 00:09:58,521
Yeah, can you turn it off?

171
00:09:58,601 --> 00:09:59,801
Turn what off?

172
00:10:00,001 --> 00:10:01,641
The suit. Just... Just please.
Just turn it off.

173
00:10:01,961 --> 00:10:03,081
Why?

174
00:10:03,161 --> 00:10:04,321
It's just standing there.

175
00:10:05,001 --> 00:10:06,881
It's sick. It's disrespectful.

176
00:10:07,361 --> 00:10:08,881
Tell you what's disrespectful.

177
00:10:10,001 --> 00:10:11,041
Whatever killed him.

178
00:10:12,081 --> 00:10:14,241
Well, there was no oxygen, right?

179
00:10:15,041 --> 00:10:16,041
Before we got here?

180
00:10:17,041 --> 00:10:19,041
BILL: Didn't he just suffocate?

181
00:10:19,561 --> 00:10:21,921
Well, his tank's full.

182
00:10:22,561 --> 00:10:23,721
And...

183
00:10:26,801 --> 00:10:27,881
His field's up.

184
00:10:28,121 --> 00:10:29,201
His what?

185
00:10:29,401 --> 00:10:30,841
Force field. Keeps the air in.

186
00:10:31,041 --> 00:10:32,841
Well, look, can't we just, like,
lie him down or something?

187
00:10:32,921 --> 00:10:35,121
-I mean, this isn't right.
-No, it isn't.

188
00:10:35,481 --> 00:10:36,481
Oris it?

189
00:10:37,121 --> 00:10:39,881
Mining station. Chasm Forge. Crew of 40.

190
00:10:40,521 --> 00:10:44,001
I've got 36 records of life
signs terminated.

191
00:10:44,321 --> 00:10:47,161
Last log entry,
"Station declared non-profitable.”

192
00:10:47,641 --> 00:10:49,721
Yeah, your workers all dying
will do that for you.

193
00:10:50,161 --> 00:10:51,481
(CLANGING)

194
00:10:55,441 --> 00:10:58,841
Okay, then. Back to the TARDIS.
Lovely in there.

195
00:10:59,041 --> 00:11:01,041
-Nice and cosy.
-Yeah, yeah, he's right.

196
00:11:01,441 --> 00:11:02,481
(CLANGING CONTINUES)

197
00:11:08,441 --> 00:11:09,441
Doctor, you listening?

198
00:11:10,721 --> 00:11:11,721
Forty minus thirty-six.

199
00:11:12,321 --> 00:11:13,441
-Sorry, what?
-Equals what?

200
00:11:13,521 --> 00:11:14,921
Oh, no, I was just saying
that Nardole was...

201
00:11:15,001 --> 00:11:16,081
DOCTOR: Four.

202
00:11:16,441 --> 00:11:17,561
Four, Bill.

203
00:11:18,801 --> 00:11:19,961
Four survivors.

204
00:11:21,001 --> 00:11:22,361
One distress call.

205
00:11:23,521 --> 00:11:26,081
The universe show its true face
when it asks for help.

206
00:11:26,161 --> 00:11:28,561
We show ours by how we respond.

207
00:11:35,721 --> 00:11:36,721
Any questions?

208
00:11:37,641 --> 00:11:38,681
Good.

209
00:11:39,561 --> 00:11:40,841
NARDOLE: Mmm-mmm.

210
00:11:42,521 --> 00:11:43,801
(DISTANT CREAKING)

211
00:11:56,401 --> 00:11:57,401
Hello.

212
00:12:16,121 --> 00:12:17,441
Has he got his tunes on?

213
00:12:17,801 --> 00:12:18,881
Not exactly.

214
00:12:21,441 --> 00:12:22,601
(BOTH EXCLAIM)

215
00:12:24,281 --> 00:12:25,441
Calm down, it's empty.

216
00:12:25,561 --> 00:12:27,641
And you couldn't just tell us?

217
00:12:27,721 --> 00:12:28,801
Are you trying to scare us?

218
00:12:28,921 --> 00:12:30,281
I'm maxing out your adrenaline.

219
00:12:30,481 --> 00:12:32,481
Fear keeps you fast. Fast is good.

220
00:12:32,561 --> 00:12:34,641
-Do people ever hit you?
-Well, only when I'm talking.

221
00:12:36,161 --> 00:12:37,681
BILL: So it's basically a robot?

222
00:12:37,761 --> 00:12:39,601
-DOCTOR: Er, well.
-Ew.

223
00:12:39,681 --> 00:12:41,401
Sort of. Fairly dumb.

224
00:12:41,961 --> 00:12:43,201
Capable of simple tasks.

225
00:12:43,281 --> 00:12:45,121
You better watch your step.
You could be out of a job.

226
00:12:45,681 --> 00:12:47,841
And... Ah! Speech.

227
00:12:49,441 --> 00:12:50,481
Hello, suit.

228
00:12:50,561 --> 00:12:53,001
AUTOMATED FEMALE VOICE: (FROM SUIT)
Good morning. How may I assist?

229
00:12:53,081 --> 00:12:54,961
Ooh, I recognise that voice.

230
00:12:55,641 --> 00:12:57,721
Yes, nice girl. Actress.

231
00:12:58,161 --> 00:13:00,881
Bit orange.
Left me for an Al in a call centre.

232
00:13:00,961 --> 00:13:02,401
What killed the crew of this station?

233
00:13:02,481 --> 00:13:04,881
I am unaware of any recent deaths.

234
00:13:04,961 --> 00:13:06,961
What about the oxygen?
Where did it all go?

235
00:13:07,041 --> 00:13:09,961
There has never been
any oxygen in this station.

236
00:13:10,521 --> 00:13:11,921
No? (LAUGHING) Listen to that.

237
00:13:12,441 --> 00:13:14,921
-Still saucy after all these years.
-DOCTOR: Explain.

238
00:13:15,441 --> 00:13:19,841
Oxygen is available for personal use
only at competitive prices.

239
00:13:20,961 --> 00:13:22,081
It's only in the suits.

240
00:13:23,121 --> 00:13:24,241
Personal use.

241
00:13:24,361 --> 00:13:27,521
They only have oxygen
in the suits themselves.

242
00:13:27,681 --> 00:13:31,161
Any unlicensed oxygen
will be automatically expelled

243
00:13:31,241 --> 00:13:32,721
to protect market value.

244
00:13:32,841 --> 00:13:34,241
NARDOLE: Charging for the air
you breathe?

245
00:13:34,681 --> 00:13:37,081
She hasn't changed. What was her name?

246
00:13:37,161 --> 00:13:38,161
BILL: Hang on.

247
00:13:38,841 --> 00:13:40,321
Didn't we just feel the space with air?

248
00:13:40,641 --> 00:13:43,161
Yes, I suppose we did.

249
00:13:43,281 --> 00:13:44,281
BILL: Because...

250
00:13:45,041 --> 00:13:46,441
It said "expelled."”

251
00:13:47,001 --> 00:13:48,161
(ALARM BLARING)

252
00:13:48,241 --> 00:13:49,241
What's that?

253
00:13:55,321 --> 00:13:56,321
It's decompressing!

254
00:13:56,441 --> 00:13:57,441
What?

255
00:14:00,681 --> 00:14:01,721
(AIR WHOOSHING)

256
00:14:01,801 --> 00:14:03,401
(SHOUTING)

257
00:14:19,641 --> 00:14:21,241
(GRUNTING)

258
00:14:22,881 --> 00:14:24,601
(GROANS, SIGHS)

259
00:14:24,961 --> 00:14:26,441
Sir.

260
00:14:26,521 --> 00:14:29,401
The TARDIS is on the other side of that.

261
00:14:29,481 --> 00:14:31,801
Yes, I was really hoping
that someone would state the obvious.

262
00:14:31,881 --> 00:14:34,601
-Vacuum behind it. Can't open it.
-(BREATHING HEAVILY)

263
00:14:34,681 --> 00:14:36,001
Oh, you're on a roll.

264
00:14:36,081 --> 00:14:39,201
And if we could,
we'd be sucked out into space.

265
00:14:39,361 --> 00:14:40,681
(DISTANT WHOOSHING)

266
00:14:41,681 --> 00:14:42,681
What's that?

267
00:14:43,161 --> 00:14:44,161
Er...

268
00:14:44,841 --> 00:14:45,841
Nothing to worry about.

269
00:14:46,041 --> 00:14:47,281
Really?

270
00:14:47,361 --> 00:14:49,041
Yes, not for several minutes.

271
00:14:49,121 --> 00:14:50,481
Well, don't stress early.

272
00:14:50,601 --> 00:14:52,441
-It's a waste of energy.
-Stress about what?

273
00:14:52,641 --> 00:14:55,041
MAN: (OVER INTERCOM) Occupants of repair
station, please identify.

274
00:14:55,161 --> 00:14:57,401
Occupants of repair station,
please identify.

275
00:14:58,281 --> 00:15:00,281
-(BEEPS)
-Hello, there. You first.

276
00:15:00,361 --> 00:15:03,121
-I'm sorry?
-Well, all your crew mates are dead.

277
00:15:03,201 --> 00:15:05,521
So either you're extremely lucky
or you killed them. Which is it?

278
00:15:05,601 --> 00:15:09,441
This is Drill Chief Tasker
and I haven't killed anyone. Yet.

279
00:15:09,681 --> 00:15:12,041
-Now, who is this?
-Doctor, plus two.

280
00:15:12,801 --> 00:15:14,281
You sent out a distress call.

281
00:15:14,961 --> 00:15:16,921
You should be expecting company.

282
00:15:17,001 --> 00:15:19,401
Now tell me, what happened to the crew
of this station?

283
00:15:19,601 --> 00:15:22,001
Hang on.
You're in the repair bay, right?

284
00:15:22,081 --> 00:15:23,761
(INHALES SHARPLY) Get out of there. Now.

285
00:15:23,841 --> 00:15:24,841
Why?

286
00:15:24,921 --> 00:15:26,161
There are suits in there.
For God's sake...

287
00:15:26,961 --> 00:15:28,321
-Stay away from the suits.
-(BILL SCREAMS)

288
00:15:28,641 --> 00:15:29,801
(ALARM BLARING)

289
00:15:30,281 --> 00:15:31,561
(ELECTRICITY CRACKLING)

290
00:15:36,881 --> 00:15:38,001
(PANTING)

291
00:15:43,521 --> 00:15:45,921
(GROANS)

292
00:15:50,241 --> 00:15:52,281
-Doctor!
-It's fried. Should be safe.

293
00:15:52,361 --> 00:15:53,721
Well, you thought you were safe before.

294
00:15:53,801 --> 00:15:55,961
Yes, well, I'm bound
to be right eventually, aren't I?

295
00:16:00,161 --> 00:16:01,401
Get me some history.

296
00:16:02,241 --> 00:16:04,201
-(BILL GASPING)
-You okay?

297
00:16:04,281 --> 00:16:07,401
(STAMMERING) Yeah. Just...
Just a little freaked, I think.

298
00:16:07,481 --> 00:16:09,521
DOCTOR: Try not to breathe so fast.

299
00:16:10,761 --> 00:16:13,361
A single line of instruction
was sent to all suits.

300
00:16:13,761 --> 00:16:15,681
"Deactivate your organic component.”

301
00:16:16,681 --> 00:16:17,961
-"Organic component"?
-Yeah.

302
00:16:18,041 --> 00:16:19,121
As in, people?

303
00:16:19,201 --> 00:16:20,881
-Ooh.
-DOCTOR: Interesting.

304
00:16:21,321 --> 00:16:23,041
They were killed by their own suits.

305
00:16:23,321 --> 00:16:24,401
Can you fry those ones, too?

306
00:16:25,041 --> 00:16:26,481
-(BEEPS)
-Possibly.

307
00:16:26,561 --> 00:16:27,921
But we have another problem.

308
00:16:28,241 --> 00:16:31,241
Opening the airlock
was the station's Plan A.

309
00:16:31,441 --> 00:16:35,081
Plan B, filtering out all the oxygen.

310
00:16:35,481 --> 00:16:37,081
So they can sell it back to us.

311
00:16:38,001 --> 00:16:40,161
Capitalism in space.

312
00:16:41,401 --> 00:16:44,561
If we want to keep breathing,
we have exactly one option.

313
00:16:46,001 --> 00:16:47,481
Buy the merchandise.

314
00:16:47,961 --> 00:16:50,121
SUIT: Oxygen levels
are seriously depleted.

315
00:16:50,361 --> 00:16:54,401
Please step on board your Ganymede
System Series 12 smart suit.

316
00:16:54,841 --> 00:16:57,281
Engage pressure pad
to activate customised robing.

317
00:16:58,161 --> 00:16:59,761
You said those things
were gonna kill us.

318
00:16:59,841 --> 00:17:01,201
Well, on the bright side,
we're dying already.

319
00:17:01,281 --> 00:17:02,561
How does this help?

320
00:17:02,641 --> 00:17:05,361
We know that they killed their occupants
on specific orders.

321
00:17:05,441 --> 00:17:07,841
I think these ones
are off-network for repairs.

322
00:17:07,921 --> 00:17:09,361
So they can't receive commands.

323
00:17:09,441 --> 00:17:10,441
What if you're wrong?

324
00:17:10,521 --> 00:17:12,361
Well, we'll be horribly murdered.

325
00:17:12,601 --> 00:17:14,161
-(GASPS) What?
-Let's say I'm right.

326
00:17:14,241 --> 00:17:17,561
Doctor, if those suits
have killed 36 people,

327
00:17:17,641 --> 00:17:20,761
that means there's 36 corpses
walking about this station.

328
00:17:21,041 --> 00:17:23,281
You know,
that really doesn't matter right now.

329
00:17:23,361 --> 00:17:24,721
Correction. Yeah, it does.

330
00:17:25,281 --> 00:17:26,881
Because I think there's something
moving out there.

331
00:17:30,601 --> 00:17:31,601
BILL: Ooh.

332
00:17:36,081 --> 00:17:37,681
Suits. Now.

333
00:17:42,201 --> 00:17:45,481
SUIT: Welcome to the Ganymede System
Series 12 smart suit.

334
00:17:45,561 --> 00:17:47,241
Oxygen field engaged.

335
00:17:48,841 --> 00:17:53,601
At current levels of exertion,
you have 2,500 breaths available.

336
00:17:54,041 --> 00:17:55,041
BILL: Breaths?

337
00:17:55,241 --> 00:17:56,841
They couldn't just give it
to me in minutes?

338
00:17:56,921 --> 00:17:57,921
It don't work like that.

339
00:17:58,201 --> 00:18:00,161
When you panic, you breathe quicker.

340
00:18:00,241 --> 00:18:01,321
You die quicker.

341
00:18:01,401 --> 00:18:04,401
Yeah, the scareder you are,
the faster you suffocate.

342
00:18:04,601 --> 00:18:06,321
So, relax or die.

343
00:18:06,681 --> 00:18:07,801
Sorry.

344
00:18:07,881 --> 00:18:09,241
Probably not the most helpful thought.

345
00:18:09,681 --> 00:18:11,321
-(EXHALES)
-So, er... Breathe in.

346
00:18:11,401 --> 00:18:12,601
Huh? (INHALES SHARPLY)

347
00:18:13,961 --> 00:18:16,521
-Breathe out.
-Drill Chief Tasker, do you read me?

348
00:18:16,601 --> 00:18:18,001
-TASKER: Read you, Doctor.
-Breathe in...

349
00:18:18,081 --> 00:18:20,681
You need to take Corridor
12 to Processing.

350
00:18:20,761 --> 00:18:21,841
-Quickly.
-DOCTOR: Come on.

351
00:18:21,921 --> 00:18:23,481
We better go. Come on.
But keep breathing.

352
00:18:26,641 --> 00:18:27,521
(DOOR OPENING)

353
00:18:27,841 --> 00:18:29,321
DOCTOR: They're here!

354
00:18:29,401 --> 00:18:30,561
Come on, this way.

355
00:18:30,641 --> 00:18:32,441
BILL'S SUIT:
You look like you're trying to run.

356
00:18:32,521 --> 00:18:34,081
Would you like some help with that?

357
00:18:34,161 --> 00:18:37,641
-Can you shut your girlfriend up?
-Velma, that was her name.

358
00:18:37,721 --> 00:18:40,561
BILL'S SUIT: Confirmed.
My name is now Velma.

359
00:18:40,641 --> 00:18:41,641
(BANGING ON DOOR)

360
00:18:45,761 --> 00:18:47,881
(ALL PANTING)

361
00:18:48,281 --> 00:18:49,521
(BANGING ON DOOR)

362
00:18:50,161 --> 00:18:51,161
(GRUNTS)

363
00:18:53,721 --> 00:18:56,121
We've hit a sealed door at the end
of Corridor 12. No way through.

364
00:18:56,481 --> 00:18:57,841
My suit's really called Velma?

365
00:18:57,921 --> 00:18:59,761
Correct. My name is Velma.

366
00:19:00,401 --> 00:19:01,401
Tasker, come in.

367
00:19:01,601 --> 00:19:02,681
NARDOLE: Oh, they're through.

368
00:19:02,761 --> 00:19:04,161
-(BILL PANTING)
-NARDOLE: Anyone?

369
00:19:04,641 --> 00:19:06,641
(PANTING) Breathe in, breathe out.

370
00:19:06,841 --> 00:19:08,641
-Hello.
-Breathe in, breathe out.

371
00:19:09,281 --> 00:19:11,641
-Breathe in, breathe out.
-NARDOLE: Anybody?

372
00:19:11,721 --> 00:19:12,721
Tasker!

373
00:19:14,601 --> 00:19:15,961
(BREATHING RAPIDLY)

374
00:19:16,041 --> 00:19:17,041
DOCTOR: Tasker.

375
00:19:17,401 --> 00:19:18,521
BILL: Breathe out!

376
00:19:19,721 --> 00:19:21,681
BILL: Breathe out! Help me!

377
00:19:24,761 --> 00:19:26,001
WOMAN: Deadlock the door.

378
00:19:26,641 --> 00:19:28,441
Cutting it a bit fine, weren't we?

379
00:19:28,521 --> 00:19:30,281
There was some debate over
whether to open it at all.

380
00:19:31,761 --> 00:19:33,641
(EXCLAIMS) Er, sorry.

381
00:19:34,041 --> 00:19:35,881
(STAMMERS) I wasn't expecting...

382
00:19:38,361 --> 00:19:39,361
Hello.

383
00:19:40,001 --> 00:19:41,441
Great, we rescued a racist.

384
00:19:41,561 --> 00:19:42,561
What? Excuse me?

385
00:19:42,681 --> 00:19:44,841
-And you are?
-We got your distress call.

386
00:19:45,921 --> 00:19:47,881
Sorry.
It's just that I haven't seen many...

387
00:19:48,521 --> 00:19:50,401
Well, any of your people. (CHUCKLES)

388
00:19:50,841 --> 00:19:51,841
It shows.

389
00:19:52,041 --> 00:19:54,001
-They're from the union.
-The union's a myth.

390
00:19:54,201 --> 00:19:55,201
Take a look.

391
00:19:56,441 --> 00:19:59,081
Yeah, we're from the mythical union.

392
00:19:59,441 --> 00:20:00,481
Dahh-Ren.

393
00:20:00,921 --> 00:20:01,921
We're here to help.

394
00:20:02,841 --> 00:20:03,921
Sorry, is your name Darren?

395
00:20:04,121 --> 00:20:05,281
(STRESSING) Dahh-Ren.

396
00:20:05,841 --> 00:20:08,721
-Oh. Makes more sense.
-(SUIT WHIRRING)

397
00:20:09,121 --> 00:20:11,361
(STAMMERS) Ah, that's not me.
That... That's not me.

398
00:20:11,801 --> 00:20:13,601
It's just glitching. Ivan.

399
00:20:13,961 --> 00:20:14,961
Take a look.

400
00:20:18,241 --> 00:20:20,721
Look, for the record,
I'm not prejudiced.

401
00:20:20,801 --> 00:20:23,281
-I'm usually on the receiving end.
-Oh, why?

402
00:20:24,041 --> 00:20:25,161
What, you really don't know?

403
00:20:25,241 --> 00:20:28,321
VELMA: Would you like to give feedback
on your experience so far?

404
00:20:28,401 --> 00:20:30,521
-Would you class...
-Right, where's your ship?

405
00:20:30,601 --> 00:20:32,641
Er, we're parked just off
your repair station.

406
00:20:32,721 --> 00:20:34,321
Then you might as well be on the moon.

407
00:20:34,401 --> 00:20:36,521
-They're swarming round there now.
-TASKER: It's just maths now.

408
00:20:36,881 --> 00:20:38,481
Oxygen divided by bodies.

409
00:20:39,081 --> 00:20:41,561
None of us have more
than 3,000 breaths left.

410
00:20:41,681 --> 00:20:42,681
Then stop wasting them.

411
00:20:42,921 --> 00:20:44,401
-(SIGHS)
-I need a map of the base.

412
00:20:44,481 --> 00:20:46,161
And a full rundown
of what happened here.

413
00:20:46,241 --> 00:20:47,521
Who the hell put you in charge?

414
00:20:47,721 --> 00:20:48,921
I'm here to save your lives,

415
00:20:49,001 --> 00:20:50,881
but if you don't want me to,
just raise your hand.

416
00:20:53,921 --> 00:20:56,721
Abby. Get the man a map.

417
00:21:00,881 --> 00:21:02,241
(EXHALES)

418
00:21:03,441 --> 00:21:04,601
All right?

419
00:21:04,721 --> 00:21:05,841
(CHUCKLES AWKWARDLY)

420
00:21:06,881 --> 00:21:08,001
Some of my best friends are bluish.

421
00:21:16,081 --> 00:21:18,281
-Why is Velma the only one that talks?
-Velma?

422
00:21:19,001 --> 00:21:20,001
My suit.

423
00:21:20,601 --> 00:21:24,121
The others do sometimes.
Mostly to say, "Here's the bill."

424
00:21:24,641 --> 00:21:27,161
(CHUCKLES) Is there a mute button?

425
00:21:28,081 --> 00:21:30,001
Yours isn't working.

426
00:21:30,081 --> 00:21:32,281
Suit's a mess.
Needs a complete overhaul.

427
00:21:33,561 --> 00:21:35,001
-(PNEUMATIC HISSING)
-(SIGHS)

428
00:21:35,281 --> 00:21:36,521
BILL: Thanks, mate.

429
00:21:37,201 --> 00:21:38,361
Don't mention it.

430
00:21:39,841 --> 00:21:42,041
DOCTOR: "Deactivate
your organic component.”

431
00:21:42,121 --> 00:21:44,121
TASKER: All the suits got
the same command.

432
00:21:44,201 --> 00:21:45,961
Best guess, someone hacked the network.

433
00:21:46,081 --> 00:21:48,121
-And you survived how?
-ABBY: We were off-network.

434
00:21:48,961 --> 00:21:50,721
You have to be to repair the conveyors.

435
00:21:50,801 --> 00:21:52,641
It was just dumb luck.

436
00:21:53,601 --> 00:21:55,081
DOCTOR: The measurements.

437
00:21:55,161 --> 00:21:57,801
-Are these in metres?
-Average breaths.

438
00:21:57,881 --> 00:22:00,841
-The only unit worth a damn out here.
-Of course they are.

439
00:22:00,921 --> 00:22:02,441
Forty breaths to the dorms.

440
00:22:02,521 --> 00:22:03,561
One-twenty to the core.

441
00:22:04,161 --> 00:22:06,481
That's where we're headed.
It's the safest place.

442
00:22:06,561 --> 00:22:09,121
Are there more suits
inside the base, or out?

443
00:22:09,201 --> 00:22:10,521
Outside is suicide.

444
00:22:10,761 --> 00:22:14,921
Inside we can move faster than them.
Outside, they have the edge.

445
00:22:15,001 --> 00:22:16,841
-Which means we're dead.
-NARDOLE: What are you mining?

446
00:22:17,161 --> 00:22:18,681
Is it worth stealing?

447
00:22:18,761 --> 00:22:20,001
You think this is a robbery?

448
00:22:20,081 --> 00:22:21,721
Well, killing you'd be a good
start if it was.

449
00:22:21,801 --> 00:22:23,121
NARDOLE: It's how I'd do it.

450
00:22:24,121 --> 00:22:28,081
If I was to do that sort of thing,
which, actually, I probably wouldn't.

451
00:22:28,161 --> 00:22:29,681
So, please don't worry.

452
00:22:29,761 --> 00:22:31,401
Well, they picked a fine day for it.

453
00:22:31,841 --> 00:22:34,201
This is the least productive
we've all been for months.

454
00:22:34,721 --> 00:22:35,961
Look, we're mining copper ore.

455
00:22:36,041 --> 00:22:39,241
You'd need to steal a mountain
to make it worth your while.

456
00:22:41,121 --> 00:22:42,961
Your employers.

457
00:22:43,041 --> 00:22:45,281
-Any help from them?
-They're too far away.

458
00:22:45,401 --> 00:22:46,561
Not that it matters.

459
00:22:47,321 --> 00:22:49,521
Whoever hacked the suits
also cut the radio.

460
00:22:50,201 --> 00:22:52,881
-DOCTOR: So your distress call...
-Was a botch.

461
00:22:52,961 --> 00:22:54,881
I boosted a suit radio through the dish.

462
00:22:56,841 --> 00:22:57,921
Good job.

463
00:23:04,121 --> 00:23:05,121
(BEEPING)

464
00:23:09,241 --> 00:23:10,921
DOCTOR: What about the brains
of these suits?

465
00:23:11,561 --> 00:23:12,561
The AL

466
00:23:13,081 --> 00:23:14,121
They're dumb as rocks.

467
00:23:15,681 --> 00:23:17,161
But can they learn?

468
00:23:17,281 --> 00:23:18,561
Evolve, grow?

469
00:23:19,441 --> 00:23:21,681
Maybe get tired
of carrying pesky humans around?

470
00:23:22,361 --> 00:23:23,361
Know the feeling?

471
00:23:23,441 --> 00:23:24,441
(CHUCKLES) Yeah.

472
00:23:24,601 --> 00:23:26,881
They've got limited problem-solving
and that's it.

473
00:23:27,801 --> 00:23:29,401
I'm missing something.
What am I missing?

474
00:23:29,841 --> 00:23:30,841
Oxygen.

475
00:23:32,201 --> 00:23:33,401
That's what we're missing.

476
00:23:33,801 --> 00:23:35,001
Maybe find some of that,

477
00:23:35,081 --> 00:23:36,521
and leave the big picture
till later, yeah?

478
00:23:41,161 --> 00:23:42,561
(BEEPING)

479
00:23:55,001 --> 00:23:56,321
(ALARM CHIMING)

480
00:24:01,681 --> 00:24:03,961
They're fixing the lock.

481
00:24:04,041 --> 00:24:05,521
Well, then it's time to go.

482
00:24:05,601 --> 00:24:07,761
Limited problem-solving, eh?

483
00:24:09,001 --> 00:24:10,361
TASKER: West corridor is free.

484
00:24:10,881 --> 00:24:12,681
Forty breaths to the core. Let's move.

485
00:24:15,401 --> 00:24:17,401
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

486
00:24:24,521 --> 00:24:26,161
Quick! They're through.

487
00:24:27,641 --> 00:24:29,641
-(ELECTRICITY CRACKLES)
-TASKER'S SUIT: Instruction received.

488
00:24:29,721 --> 00:24:32,201
Organic component will be deactivated.

489
00:24:32,481 --> 00:24:35,801
Please remain calm while
your central nervous system is disabled.

490
00:24:35,881 --> 00:24:37,641
-(SCREAMS)
-Your life is in our hands.

491
00:24:37,721 --> 00:24:38,881
-Airlock!
-(ELECTRICITY BUZZING)

492
00:24:40,201 --> 00:24:41,681
(PANTING)

493
00:24:54,521 --> 00:24:56,641
IVAN: Airlock. Helmets on.

494
00:25:00,281 --> 00:25:01,681
BILL: Where are we going?
DOCTOR: Outside.

495
00:25:01,921 --> 00:25:03,361
Well, didn't they say
that was a bad idea?

496
00:25:03,441 --> 00:25:04,561
It is.

497
00:25:05,801 --> 00:25:06,841
But I know a worse one.

498
00:25:08,881 --> 00:25:10,801
Wait. (STUTTERS) Why do I need that?

499
00:25:10,881 --> 00:25:13,601
What about the air force field thing?

500
00:25:13,681 --> 00:25:15,401
Not strong enough for a vacuum.

501
00:25:15,481 --> 00:25:16,481
Trust me.

502
00:25:23,121 --> 00:25:24,161
(BILL GASPS)

503
00:25:26,721 --> 00:25:28,241
What happens if I throw up in my helmet?

504
00:25:28,881 --> 00:25:30,721
Colour and smells.

505
00:25:31,481 --> 00:25:33,401
Don't throw up in helmet. Check.

506
00:25:38,321 --> 00:25:39,721
(ALARM CHIMES)

507
00:25:42,761 --> 00:25:44,641
VELMA: Warning. Helmet malfunction.

508
00:25:44,721 --> 00:25:45,961
BILL: Er, Doctor?

509
00:25:46,041 --> 00:25:47,641
Please advise local technician.

510
00:25:47,881 --> 00:25:48,881
BILL: Somebody, stop it!

511
00:25:50,041 --> 00:25:52,361
-Put it back on!
-Doctor, that's not me doing that.

512
00:25:52,441 --> 00:25:54,121
-Put it back on!
-I'm trying.

513
00:25:54,481 --> 00:25:55,521
I can't move my arms.

514
00:25:57,321 --> 00:25:58,361
Stop the cycle.

515
00:25:58,441 --> 00:26:00,601
We can't stop it. It's automated.

516
00:26:00,921 --> 00:26:02,801
DOCTOR: Then we know
why your ship was being repaired.

517
00:26:02,881 --> 00:26:04,401
Bill. Bill!

518
00:26:04,681 --> 00:26:06,641
You're about to be exposed
to the vacuum of space.

519
00:26:07,161 --> 00:26:08,361
Oh, God.

520
00:26:08,481 --> 00:26:10,081
So don't hold your breath.

521
00:26:10,561 --> 00:26:11,841
Or my lungs will explode.

522
00:26:11,921 --> 00:26:13,721
You were listening. Well done.

523
00:26:17,681 --> 00:26:18,921
BILL: What are we gonna do?

524
00:26:19,001 --> 00:26:20,241
(PNEUMATIC HISSING)

525
00:27:01,441 --> 00:27:03,201
(HIGH-PITCHED TONE)

526
00:27:12,001 --> 00:27:13,521
(WHITE NOISE BLARING)

527
00:27:42,361 --> 00:27:44,321
Argh. (GRUNTS)

528
00:27:48,521 --> 00:27:50,041
(CHUCKLES HOARSELY)

529
00:27:56,681 --> 00:27:57,681
(WHISPERING) Suit.

530
00:27:58,881 --> 00:27:59,961
Suit!

531
00:28:00,721 --> 00:28:02,401
-Velma.
-VELMA: Good morning.

532
00:28:02,881 --> 00:28:04,441
-How may I assist?
-Shh. Shh.

533
00:28:05,321 --> 00:28:06,321
I can't move.

534
00:28:06,401 --> 00:28:10,321
This suit is currently offline
for diagnostic purposes.

535
00:28:11,721 --> 00:28:12,961
(BEEPING)

536
00:28:19,001 --> 00:28:21,801
Oh, Nardole, Ivan, thank God!

537
00:28:22,361 --> 00:28:24,481
You're awake. Told you.

538
00:28:24,601 --> 00:28:25,601
Are you okay?

539
00:28:26,161 --> 00:28:27,161
No.

540
00:28:28,481 --> 00:28:29,841
(WHISPERS) What happened? I can't move.

541
00:28:31,121 --> 00:28:33,721
Well, your suit is set to auto.

542
00:28:34,081 --> 00:28:35,841
The Doctor hacked it and walked you out.

543
00:28:35,921 --> 00:28:37,641
NARDOLE: Ah,
and you've got oxygen deprivation,

544
00:28:37,721 --> 00:28:39,121
which is why you feel...

545
00:28:39,201 --> 00:28:40,921
-Like you feel.
-Have you looked down there?

546
00:28:41,001 --> 00:28:42,001
NARDOLE: Hmm?

547
00:28:42,521 --> 00:28:43,961
Ah, no, they're fine.

548
00:28:44,521 --> 00:28:45,521
What?

549
00:28:46,241 --> 00:28:48,241
Are we safe? What's stopping them?

550
00:28:48,521 --> 00:28:49,801
This whole area's new.

551
00:28:50,561 --> 00:28:51,961
It's not in their mapping system.

552
00:28:52,041 --> 00:28:53,441
Hmm, see?

553
00:28:54,521 --> 00:28:57,801
You know, like when your satnav
doesn't know a new road.

554
00:28:58,281 --> 00:28:59,441
BILL: So they can't come here?

555
00:28:59,601 --> 00:29:00,761
IVAN: Not without a floor plan.

556
00:29:02,601 --> 00:29:03,601
BILL: Good.

557
00:29:04,281 --> 00:29:05,721
What happened to the Doctor?

558
00:29:05,801 --> 00:29:07,081
-I thought I saw...
-Yeah, he...

559
00:29:07,641 --> 00:29:09,201
The Doctor took you to safety.

560
00:29:09,281 --> 00:29:10,601
He gave you his helmet.

561
00:29:11,201 --> 00:29:12,841
-He died?
-He should have done.

562
00:29:13,961 --> 00:29:15,161
Don't know how he survived.

563
00:29:18,481 --> 00:29:19,961
Listen. About the Doctor...

564
00:29:20,481 --> 00:29:23,641
He walked in a vacuum for far too long.

565
00:29:23,721 --> 00:29:25,201
He's mostly okay,

566
00:29:26,401 --> 00:29:27,401
but he paid a price.

567
00:29:27,481 --> 00:29:28,481
What do you mean?

568
00:29:28,921 --> 00:29:30,161
He's in Section 12.

569
00:29:33,481 --> 00:29:35,201
(BEEPING)

570
00:29:43,681 --> 00:29:44,681
Doctor?

571
00:29:48,441 --> 00:29:49,441
Bill.

572
00:29:50,561 --> 00:29:51,561
You're up.

573
00:29:51,721 --> 00:29:52,721
You're blind.

574
00:29:52,801 --> 00:29:56,001
I am? Oh, that explains
the bruised shins.

575
00:29:57,201 --> 00:29:59,161
Oh, don't go all gooey on me.

576
00:29:59,921 --> 00:30:00,921
It's temporary.

577
00:30:01,001 --> 00:30:02,401
-Really?
-Yeah.

578
00:30:03,041 --> 00:30:04,801
-Once we get back to the TARDIS...
-The TARDIS?

579
00:30:05,241 --> 00:30:07,481
Mmm. I've got stuff in there
that'll cure anything.

580
00:30:07,841 --> 00:30:10,281
Failing that, I think I've got some
spare eyes somewhere.

581
00:30:10,401 --> 00:30:11,721
They're from a lizard,
but I'm sure they'll fit.

582
00:30:12,761 --> 00:30:14,841
So, erm, until then...

583
00:30:15,201 --> 00:30:16,201
Until then what?

584
00:30:16,601 --> 00:30:18,441
You really think
this is going to slow me down?

585
00:30:19,161 --> 00:30:21,441
I do most of my best work
ordering other people around.

586
00:30:21,521 --> 00:30:24,441
NARDOLE: (SCOFFS)
You do know we're still here, right?

587
00:30:24,521 --> 00:30:26,121
AUTOMATED FEMALE VOICE:
Mining station Chasm Forge...

588
00:30:26,201 --> 00:30:27,841
Didn't I send you out to get me a latte?

589
00:30:29,481 --> 00:30:30,641
So what's the plan?

590
00:30:31,281 --> 00:30:34,841
Well, we've all been trying to get
a radio working and the Doctor's been...

591
00:30:36,481 --> 00:30:37,481
Thinking.

592
00:30:37,681 --> 00:30:40,161
Don't mean to hurry you,
but in 700 breaths, I'll be dead.

593
00:30:40,961 --> 00:30:42,161
I need to think.

594
00:30:49,601 --> 00:30:51,481
He really doesn't like help.

595
00:30:52,801 --> 00:30:54,841
(MACHINE BEEPING)

596
00:30:55,441 --> 00:30:56,481
ABBY: It's a transponder.

597
00:30:57,321 --> 00:30:58,521
From a ship.

598
00:31:08,761 --> 00:31:10,961
Doctor, you okay?

599
00:31:14,001 --> 00:31:17,281
Bill, I've got no TARDIS, no sonic,
about 10 minutes' oxygen left,

600
00:31:18,041 --> 00:31:19,121
and now I'm blind.

601
00:31:20,161 --> 00:31:22,961
Can you imagine how unbearable
I'm going to be when I pull this off?

602
00:31:23,521 --> 00:31:24,641
Don't do this.

603
00:31:25,081 --> 00:31:26,201
You always do this.

604
00:31:26,481 --> 00:31:27,481
Do what?

605
00:31:27,761 --> 00:31:30,401
Make jokes to distract me
from whatever's about to kill us.

606
00:31:30,841 --> 00:31:32,001
What else are jokes for?

607
00:31:32,081 --> 00:31:33,121
NARDOLE: Doctor!

608
00:31:33,281 --> 00:31:35,001
There's a rescue ship on the way.

609
00:31:35,081 --> 00:31:37,081
We've picked up a company transponder.

610
00:31:37,161 --> 00:31:38,521
ABBY: If there's a rescue ship
on the way,

611
00:31:38,601 --> 00:31:40,561
then how can the rescue ship
already be here?

612
00:31:40,801 --> 00:31:42,001
Too many rescue ships.

613
00:31:42,641 --> 00:31:43,641
It's a first world problem.

614
00:31:43,881 --> 00:31:44,881
Who are you?

615
00:31:50,681 --> 00:31:51,681
I'm the Doctor.

616
00:31:52,161 --> 00:31:55,001
I will do everything in my power
to save all your lives, and when I do,

617
00:31:55,521 --> 00:31:57,641
you will spend the rest of them
wondering who I was,

618
00:31:58,121 --> 00:31:59,241
and why I helped you.

619
00:32:00,561 --> 00:32:02,361
If anyone's offering a better deal,
be my guest.

620
00:32:02,641 --> 00:32:03,921
You didn't save Tasker, did you?

621
00:32:04,641 --> 00:32:05,641
And he believed you.

622
00:32:06,001 --> 00:32:07,641
Trusted you.

623
00:32:07,721 --> 00:32:08,801
And now he's dead.

624
00:32:10,041 --> 00:32:13,681
Can you give me one good reason
why you shouldn't join him?

625
00:32:13,761 --> 00:32:15,961
Whoa, whoa, we're all getting
a little punchy here.

626
00:32:16,041 --> 00:32:18,081
It's the oxygen thinning.
It's making it harder to think.

627
00:32:18,161 --> 00:32:19,321
DAHH-REN'S SUIT: Instruction received.

628
00:32:19,401 --> 00:32:20,881
-You get out of my way.
-Complying.

629
00:32:20,961 --> 00:32:23,921
Please remain calm while
your central nervous system is disabled.

630
00:32:24,361 --> 00:32:26,561
-Your life is in our hands.
-(YELLING)

631
00:32:26,641 --> 00:32:28,281
ABBY: Head to the reactor core. Run!

632
00:32:29,201 --> 00:32:30,921
-What's happening?
-Guess.

633
00:32:36,361 --> 00:32:37,921
IVAN: They knew we were there somehow.

634
00:32:38,361 --> 00:32:39,801
Voice rec. Had to be.

635
00:32:41,561 --> 00:32:43,161
Doctor? Doctor, my suit!

636
00:32:43,401 --> 00:32:44,481
It's doing it again.

637
00:32:44,841 --> 00:32:46,121
I...I can't move.

638
00:32:47,561 --> 00:32:50,001
IVAN: The sequencer's jammed.
Needs a reboot.

639
00:32:50,081 --> 00:32:51,881
-How long will that take?
-Too long.

640
00:32:52,121 --> 00:32:54,001
Okay, we'll pick her up, come on.

641
00:32:55,121 --> 00:32:57,241
VELMA: Warning.
This is an illegal manoeuver.

642
00:32:57,321 --> 00:32:59,121
The suit won't let us.
Health and safety.

643
00:32:59,201 --> 00:33:00,281
Health and safety?

644
00:33:01,001 --> 00:33:02,001
Doctor?

645
00:33:02,081 --> 00:33:04,561
Okay, get her out of the suit.
Give her mine.

646
00:33:04,641 --> 00:33:07,041
The sequencer controls the release
clamps. We can't get her out.

647
00:33:07,121 --> 00:33:08,681
Well, we can't leave her here.
they'll kill her!

648
00:33:08,761 --> 00:33:11,761
VELMA: Please do not interfere
with the operation of this suit.

649
00:33:11,841 --> 00:33:13,001
Fines may be incurred.

650
00:33:13,081 --> 00:33:14,801
Great, I get fined for dying.

651
00:33:14,921 --> 00:33:16,161
Fined for dying.

652
00:33:18,481 --> 00:33:19,481
Doctor?

653
00:33:19,761 --> 00:33:21,561
What if there was never a hack?

654
00:33:22,321 --> 00:33:25,681
What if this is just business?
Business as usual?

655
00:33:26,081 --> 00:33:27,201
What do you mean?

656
00:33:28,401 --> 00:33:30,401
Bill. Bill, do you trust me?

657
00:33:30,481 --> 00:33:31,801
Why are you saying that?

658
00:33:31,881 --> 00:33:33,281
We're gonna have to leave you here.

659
00:33:33,841 --> 00:33:34,881
What?

660
00:33:35,321 --> 00:33:36,841
-I'll die.
-You're not gonna die.

661
00:33:37,041 --> 00:33:39,081
But I won't lie to you.
This will not be good.

662
00:33:39,161 --> 00:33:40,521
We have to go, now.

663
00:33:40,841 --> 00:33:41,921
You will go through hell.

664
00:33:42,001 --> 00:33:44,401
But you will come through it
and I will be waiting on the other side.

665
00:33:44,481 --> 00:33:45,841
But if I was going to die...

666
00:33:45,921 --> 00:33:48,321
-You are not going to die!
-Wouldn't you just say exactly the same?

667
00:33:50,401 --> 00:33:52,321
I will see you soon.

668
00:33:53,361 --> 00:33:55,401
Could you just tell me
a joke before you go?

669
00:33:57,561 --> 00:33:59,281
(YELLS) Would you just tell me a joke?

670
00:34:00,801 --> 00:34:02,601
He didn't tell me a joke.

671
00:34:03,521 --> 00:34:05,121
Is that a good thing or a bad thing?

672
00:34:05,641 --> 00:34:07,001
Mum, answer me!

673
00:34:09,481 --> 00:34:10,921
(BEEPING)

674
00:34:12,721 --> 00:34:14,321
-(ELECTRICITY CRACKLING)
-(WHIMPERS)

675
00:34:14,401 --> 00:34:16,681
-VELMA: Instruction received. Complying.
-(SCREAMS)

676
00:34:17,201 --> 00:34:19,881
Please remain calm while
your central nervous system is disabled.

677
00:34:21,161 --> 00:34:23,241
Your life is in our hands.

678
00:34:52,281 --> 00:34:54,281
Doctor, this isn't gonna work.

679
00:34:54,361 --> 00:34:55,601
(PANTING) Isn't it?

680
00:34:56,441 --> 00:34:57,481
Why, what do you think I'm doing?

681
00:34:58,241 --> 00:34:59,281
Electrolysis.

682
00:34:59,361 --> 00:35:00,921
Splitting water into hydrogen
and oxygen.

683
00:35:01,361 --> 00:35:02,721
Oh, that's clever.

684
00:35:02,921 --> 00:35:04,281
I wish I could see me doing that.

685
00:35:04,561 --> 00:35:06,601
Doctor, that water is cooling
the nuclear core.

686
00:35:07,001 --> 00:35:11,001
We'd enjoy five minutes of oxygen before
the whole thing overheated and blew.

687
00:35:11,121 --> 00:35:14,241
Yes, five whole minutes.

688
00:35:15,481 --> 00:35:16,961
We could boil the hell out of an egg.

689
00:35:18,801 --> 00:35:20,201
Stop being such a quitter.

690
00:35:21,161 --> 00:35:23,921
Doctor, it wasn't your fault.
You couldn't have saved her.

691
00:35:25,521 --> 00:35:27,161
Do you know what's wrong
with this universe?

692
00:35:27,481 --> 00:35:29,641
Believe me, I've looked into it.

693
00:35:30,641 --> 00:35:34,441
Everyone says it's not their fault.

694
00:35:34,801 --> 00:35:37,001
Well, yes, it is.

695
00:35:37,401 --> 00:35:40,801
All of it. It's all your fault.

696
00:35:40,881 --> 00:35:42,161
So what are you gonna do about it?

697
00:35:42,241 --> 00:35:44,881
There's nothing we can do. She's dead.

698
00:35:46,561 --> 00:35:50,201
She's no more dead than you are,
than I am,

699
00:35:50,601 --> 00:35:52,281
than everyone on this station is.

700
00:35:53,521 --> 00:35:54,721
Get me to a keyboard.

701
00:35:54,801 --> 00:35:56,081
What? Why?

702
00:35:56,161 --> 00:35:57,961
Because I'm not trying
to make oxygen. Keyboard.

703
00:35:58,321 --> 00:35:59,961
(PANTING) Now. Please.

704
00:36:01,081 --> 00:36:02,441
You think you have a plan?

705
00:36:02,921 --> 00:36:04,481
We've got exactly one plan left.

706
00:36:04,561 --> 00:36:06,241
-What plan?
-The big one.

707
00:36:06,481 --> 00:36:08,241
The one that you've been waiting for
all your life.

708
00:36:08,321 --> 00:36:09,561
-What's he doing?
-(KEYBOARD CLACKING)

709
00:36:09,641 --> 00:36:11,001
Cooling system again.

710
00:36:11,401 --> 00:36:14,001
DOCTOR: Yes.
I've rejigged it a tiny little bit.

711
00:36:14,281 --> 00:36:15,961
Either that, or I've really
screwed up the plumbing.

712
00:36:16,041 --> 00:36:17,081
It's tough when you're blind.

713
00:36:17,161 --> 00:36:18,321
We need to know about this plan.

714
00:36:18,401 --> 00:36:19,601
Uh-huh.

715
00:36:19,681 --> 00:36:22,441
The nice thing about life is,
however bad it gets,

716
00:36:22,521 --> 00:36:25,001
there's always one
last option available.

717
00:36:27,201 --> 00:36:28,241
Dying well.

718
00:36:28,921 --> 00:36:29,921
ABBY: No.

719
00:36:30,721 --> 00:36:31,721
No!

720
00:36:31,801 --> 00:36:33,281
-What? What is it?
-Our life signs.

721
00:36:33,361 --> 00:36:34,921
He's wired them to the cooling system.

722
00:36:35,121 --> 00:36:36,761
If we die, it vents.

723
00:36:37,801 --> 00:36:39,881
When the suits kill us,
and they are going to kill us,

724
00:36:40,281 --> 00:36:43,281
the core will blow
and the whole station will be destroyed.

725
00:36:43,361 --> 00:36:44,681
One very big boom.

726
00:36:45,601 --> 00:36:47,161
Is that really the best you've got?

727
00:36:47,321 --> 00:36:48,361
Revenge?

728
00:36:48,841 --> 00:36:50,681
Not just revenge.

729
00:36:51,401 --> 00:36:53,281
It's revenge as bright as the sun.

730
00:36:54,601 --> 00:36:57,161
It's revenge you can
see across galaxies.

731
00:36:58,001 --> 00:37:00,201
Not bad for a blind man.

732
00:37:00,641 --> 00:37:02,081
He's locked us out of the subroutine.

733
00:37:02,201 --> 00:37:03,721
Oh, I'm sorry, I just thought
I was tweeting.

734
00:37:04,081 --> 00:37:05,281
They're through the third lock.

735
00:37:05,481 --> 00:37:06,521
Open the doors.

736
00:37:06,721 --> 00:37:07,801
Are you out of your mind?

737
00:37:08,521 --> 00:37:11,001
Ah, yes. Completely.
But that's not a recent thing.

738
00:37:11,281 --> 00:37:14,161
Listen.
All we've got left is a good death.

739
00:37:14,721 --> 00:37:17,081
This is the moment you've been waiting
for since the day you were born.

740
00:37:17,561 --> 00:37:18,681
Don't screw it up now.

741
00:37:18,761 --> 00:37:20,281
There's rescue ships on the way.

742
00:37:20,361 --> 00:37:21,361
DOCTOR: No, there isn't!

743
00:37:22,561 --> 00:37:23,561
No, there isn't.

744
00:37:25,721 --> 00:37:27,761
There never was a rescue ship.

745
00:37:28,121 --> 00:37:29,121
What are you talking about?

746
00:37:29,201 --> 00:37:30,201
DOCTOR: There was no hacking.

747
00:37:30,281 --> 00:37:31,281
No malfunction.

748
00:37:31,361 --> 00:37:35,681
The suits are doing
exactly what they were designed to do.

749
00:37:35,761 --> 00:37:38,001
What your employers
are telling them to do.

750
00:37:38,081 --> 00:37:39,081
And what would that be?

751
00:37:39,481 --> 00:37:42,081
Save the oxygen that you are wasting.

752
00:37:42,521 --> 00:37:44,041
You've become inefficient.

753
00:37:45,041 --> 00:37:46,161
You even told me.

754
00:37:47,361 --> 00:37:48,561
Your conveyors are down.

755
00:37:49,201 --> 00:37:50,441
So everyone had to die?

756
00:37:50,641 --> 00:37:54,321
Ha. Well, you are just organic
components

757
00:37:54,401 --> 00:37:55,961
and you're no longer efficient.

758
00:37:56,081 --> 00:37:57,641
So you're being thrown away.
You don't believe me?

759
00:37:58,441 --> 00:38:00,441
Check on that rescue ship.
Access the log.

760
00:38:00,521 --> 00:38:01,721
No, not true.

761
00:38:01,801 --> 00:38:03,641
None of it. You...
You are just a lunatic.

762
00:38:04,561 --> 00:38:05,801
It is true, Abby.

763
00:38:07,001 --> 00:38:08,441
The ship...

764
00:38:08,521 --> 00:38:10,601
It set off before the distress call.

765
00:38:12,521 --> 00:38:13,601
DOCTOR: They're not your rescuers.

766
00:38:14,241 --> 00:38:15,361
They're your replacements.

767
00:38:16,001 --> 00:38:17,561
The end point of capitalism.

768
00:38:18,521 --> 00:38:19,681
The bottom line,

769
00:38:19,761 --> 00:38:22,601
where human life has no value at all.

770
00:38:23,201 --> 00:38:24,721
We're fighting an algorithm.

771
00:38:25,441 --> 00:38:26,561
A spreadsheet.

772
00:38:26,881 --> 00:38:28,521
Like every worker, everywhere.

773
00:38:29,121 --> 00:38:30,321
We're fighting the suits.

774
00:38:30,441 --> 00:38:32,321
-(ALARM BLARING)
-They're nearly through!

775
00:38:33,561 --> 00:38:34,601
Open up.

776
00:38:35,201 --> 00:38:36,241
Let's send them a message.

777
00:38:36,321 --> 00:38:38,601
Let's teach them a lesson
they will never forget.

778
00:38:39,721 --> 00:38:41,481
If they take our lives,

779
00:38:41,561 --> 00:38:44,601
we take their station, and every penny
they will ever make from it.

780
00:38:45,241 --> 00:38:46,401
Die well.

781
00:38:46,761 --> 00:38:48,041
It's the finish line.

782
00:38:48,441 --> 00:38:49,521
It's winning.

783
00:38:51,241 --> 00:38:52,241
Open it.

784
00:38:52,321 --> 00:38:53,321
(SIGHS)

785
00:38:53,641 --> 00:38:54,881
(DOOR OPENING)

786
00:39:02,841 --> 00:39:04,081
NARDOLE: Doctor.

787
00:39:04,801 --> 00:39:06,041
-Doctor.
-What?

788
00:39:06,681 --> 00:39:07,881
It's Bill.

789
00:39:08,601 --> 00:39:09,841
Of course, it's Bill.

790
00:39:10,361 --> 00:39:12,161
Fate and me, we have a thing.
Hello, suits!

791
00:39:14,361 --> 00:39:16,801
Our deaths will be brave
and brilliant and unafraid,

792
00:39:17,721 --> 00:39:20,401
but above all, suits,
our deaths will be...

793
00:39:21,201 --> 00:39:22,481
Expensive!

794
00:39:23,841 --> 00:39:25,001
(GASPS)

795
00:39:27,881 --> 00:39:29,201
DOCTOR: Check your readings.

796
00:39:29,881 --> 00:39:33,801
We die, your precious station dies.

797
00:39:34,241 --> 00:39:35,681
The whole thing will blow.

798
00:39:36,441 --> 00:39:39,321
The company will make
the biggest loss in its history.

799
00:39:40,041 --> 00:39:42,601
A moment ago,
we were too expensive to live.

800
00:39:42,921 --> 00:39:44,681
Now we're more expensive dead.

801
00:39:44,961 --> 00:39:46,361
Welcome to the rest of your lives.

802
00:39:46,801 --> 00:39:48,241
But you said that we were gonna die.

803
00:39:48,481 --> 00:39:51,641
Ah, technically,
I said you were as dead as Bill.

804
00:39:51,921 --> 00:39:54,241
Probably should have mentioned,
Bill's not dead.

805
00:39:56,201 --> 00:39:58,041
-(PNEUMATIC HISSING)
-(GASPING)

806
00:39:59,401 --> 00:40:01,041
I saw earlier,
her suit battery was too low.

807
00:40:01,721 --> 00:40:03,401
-Not enough for a lethal dose.
-(COUGHING)

808
00:40:03,481 --> 00:40:05,121
I know what it takes to kill someone.

809
00:40:06,121 --> 00:40:07,121
Ellie.

810
00:40:08,801 --> 00:40:09,921
(EXHALES)

811
00:40:11,601 --> 00:40:12,721
What are they doing?

812
00:40:13,321 --> 00:40:14,321
DOCTOR: Relax.

813
00:40:14,921 --> 00:40:16,361
They're giving us their oxygen.

814
00:40:17,001 --> 00:40:18,161
Good for business.

815
00:40:18,241 --> 00:40:20,241
Well, I'm not sure
I'm very happy about it.

816
00:40:28,201 --> 00:40:29,361
Thank you.

817
00:40:32,001 --> 00:40:33,241
(HISSES)

818
00:40:34,721 --> 00:40:35,721
It worked.

819
00:40:36,521 --> 00:40:37,561
-Doctor.
-Yeah.

820
00:40:38,161 --> 00:40:39,201
I think I'm alive.

821
00:40:39,841 --> 00:40:42,041
Yep, you do seem to be
under that impression.

822
00:40:53,241 --> 00:40:54,401
NARDOLE: Glad, though. (CHUCKLES)

823
00:40:56,081 --> 00:40:57,201
(ELECTRONIC CHIME)

824
00:40:58,201 --> 00:41:00,361
NARDOLE: Okay, keep your eyes open.

825
00:41:01,201 --> 00:41:03,241
Keep them open up there. That's it.

826
00:41:03,761 --> 00:41:06,361
ABBY: You could have told us
your actual plan in the first place.

827
00:41:07,241 --> 00:41:10,201
I could have told Bill
her battery was too weak to kill her.

828
00:41:10,641 --> 00:41:11,961
But the suits would have heard.

829
00:41:12,721 --> 00:41:15,121
I try never to tell the enemy
my secret plan.

830
00:41:15,561 --> 00:41:17,641
Ah. Better?

831
00:41:18,761 --> 00:41:19,761
DOCTOR: Hmm.

832
00:41:21,441 --> 00:41:22,441
Ah.

833
00:41:22,841 --> 00:41:25,001
We're back in the TARDIS.
When did that happen?

834
00:41:26,521 --> 00:41:27,601
Thank you, Doctor.

835
00:41:28,521 --> 00:41:29,561
For all that you've done.

836
00:41:29,881 --> 00:41:31,481
I'm sorry that I didn't have
more faith in your methods.

837
00:41:31,561 --> 00:41:32,641
Ah, don't mention it.

838
00:41:33,161 --> 00:41:37,041
Now, I can set you down on a hub-world
outside of corporate control.

839
00:41:37,641 --> 00:41:39,481
Or anywhere, really.

840
00:41:40,361 --> 00:41:42,521
The universe is your crustacean.

841
00:41:45,201 --> 00:41:47,561
Head Office.
We've got a complaint to make.

842
00:41:49,561 --> 00:41:51,001
I think we can arrange that.

843
00:41:52,761 --> 00:41:54,001
(KEYBOARD CLACKING)

844
00:41:55,401 --> 00:41:56,521
Promise me you'll be loud.

845
00:41:56,841 --> 00:41:58,041
(CHUCKLES) Promise.

846
00:41:59,921 --> 00:42:01,601
(WHOOSHING)

847
00:42:14,841 --> 00:42:16,081
BILL: Does it work?

848
00:42:16,161 --> 00:42:17,241
DOCTOR: Does what work?

849
00:42:17,721 --> 00:42:18,881
Making a complaint to Head Office?

850
00:42:19,361 --> 00:42:20,961
No idea. I've never had a Head Office.

851
00:42:22,121 --> 00:42:24,481
But as far as I remember,
there's a successful rebellion

852
00:42:24,561 --> 00:42:25,601
six months later.

853
00:42:26,361 --> 00:42:28,201
Corporate dominance in space is history.

854
00:42:29,121 --> 00:42:30,521
And that about wraps it for capitalists.

855
00:42:30,641 --> 00:42:31,761
Hey.

856
00:42:31,841 --> 00:42:34,561
Then the human race
finds a whole new mistake.

857
00:42:35,841 --> 00:42:36,961
But that's another story.

858
00:42:37,281 --> 00:42:38,881
-Can't wait.
-But you will.

859
00:42:40,961 --> 00:42:41,961
Laters.

860
00:42:44,161 --> 00:42:45,161
Laters.

861
00:42:46,001 --> 00:42:47,121
(DOOR OPENS)

862
00:42:48,361 --> 00:42:49,801
(DOOR SHUTS)

863
00:42:51,881 --> 00:42:53,041
NARDOLE: Never again.

864
00:42:54,761 --> 00:42:56,161
Stop talking. Now.

865
00:42:56,521 --> 00:42:57,641
NARDOLE: I'm serious.

866
00:42:57,721 --> 00:43:00,201
We were so close to not making it back.

867
00:43:00,921 --> 00:43:02,041
Then what happens to the vault?

868
00:43:03,481 --> 00:43:05,121
You know what's at stake here.

869
00:43:05,961 --> 00:43:07,241
Really, stop talking.

870
00:43:07,921 --> 00:43:09,001
What if you got killed out there?

871
00:43:09,441 --> 00:43:11,921
Huh? What happens
to your precious Earth then?

872
00:43:12,841 --> 00:43:16,841
You need to be here and you need
to be ready if that door ever opens.

873
00:43:17,761 --> 00:43:19,001
-Look at me.
-I can't.

874
00:43:19,561 --> 00:43:22,001
What if you came back injured? Or sick?

875
00:43:22,801 --> 00:43:25,561
You really think our friend down there
won't know that?

876
00:43:25,641 --> 00:43:26,721
Won't sense it?

877
00:43:28,401 --> 00:43:29,441
Look at me!

878
00:43:29,521 --> 00:43:31,321
Nardole, I can't. I really can't.

879
00:43:33,801 --> 00:43:36,521
I can't look at anything ever again.

880
00:43:37,441 --> 00:43:39,281
I'm still blind.

881
00:43:40,961 --> 00:43:42,961
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

882
00:44:11,361 --> 00:44:14,601
MAN: The Pope requests most urgently
a personal audience.

883
00:44:15,281 --> 00:44:17,641
The Veritas contains a secret.

884
00:44:17,801 --> 00:44:20,521
Everyone who worked on the translation
is now dead.

885
00:44:20,641 --> 00:44:23,041
NARDOLE: You're blind
and you don't want your enemies to know.

886
00:44:23,121 --> 00:44:25,001
But why does it have to be a secret
from Bill?

887
00:44:25,281 --> 00:44:26,361
BILL: You happy in those shades?

888
00:44:26,441 --> 00:44:27,681
DOCTOR: In darkness,
we are revealed.

889
00:44:28,321 --> 00:44:30,921
MAN: Very few know this place exists.

890
00:44:31,401 --> 00:44:32,401
The Haereticum.

891
00:44:32,561 --> 00:44:34,521
DOCTOR: Something's coming, Bill.
Something very big.

892
00:44:35,441 --> 00:44:38,081
And something possibly very, very bad.

893
00:44:38,401 --> 00:44:40,721
How can I save them
when I'm lost in the dark?

